  "prompt": "Why is having a capybara as a pet illegal?",
  "response": "The legality of keeping a capybara as a pet varies by location, and it's not universally illegal. However, there are several reasons why owning a capybara can be challenging or restricted:\n\n1. Specific habitat needs: Capybaras require:\n- Large water spaces\n- Warm temperatures\n- Specific diet\n- Social interaction with other capybaras\n\n2. Exotic pet regulations: Many regions have laws restricting exotic animal ownership.\n\n3. Special care requirements:\n- High maintenance\n- Expensive to properly care for\n- Need significant space\n- Require specialized veterinary care\n\n4. Potential risks:\n- Can be aggressive\n- Might carry diseases\n- Not domesticated like traditional pets\n- Can cause property damage\n\n5. Environmental considerations:\n- Not native to many regions\n- Potential ecological impact if released\n\nSome U.S. states like Texas and Pennsylvania allow capybara ownership with proper permitting, while others strictly prohibit it. In some areas, you might need special exotic pet licenses.\n\nWhile not universally illegal, owning a capybara is complex and not recommended for most pet owners due to their specialized needs and challenging care requirements.",
